We want to find the steady states of this differential equations. To do
so, set $\frac{dm}{dt} = 0$, i.e.

\begin{align*}
16m\left(1 - \frac{m}{4}\right) -12 = 0
\end{align*}

Simplifying yields

\begin{align*}
16m - 4m^{2} -12 = 0
\end{align*}

and once more

\begin{align*}
m^{2}-4m +3 = 0
\end{align*}

Factoring yields

\begin{align*}
(m-3)(m-1) = 0
\end{align*}

and so the steady states are given by $m = 1$ and $m = 3$. It is quickly
checked, e.g. by plugging in $m = 0$, $m = 2$, and $m = 4$, that

\begin{align*}
\frac{dm}{dt} = \left\{\begin{array}{rl}
\text{negative }& \text{if } m < 1 \text{ or } m > 3, \\
0 & \text{if  } m = 1 \text{ or } m = 3, \\
\text{positive }& \text{if } 1 < m < 3.
\end{array}\right.
\end{align*}

At time $t = 0$ we have $m(0) = 2$. Hence, despite the fishing, the
population of fish will grow initially. But the growth will slow down as
the population size approaches the steady state value $m = 3$. A steady
state can never be reached in finite time, hence the answer is
\textbf{No}, the fish population will never equal 3 million.

